rique Rahman in Dhaka on Feb. 13, 2026.","caption":"A man walks past campaign posters of Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) chairman and Tarique Rahman in Dhaka on Feb. 13, 2026.","credit":"(Sajjad HUSSAIN / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=d-MzaKNt","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=9O7YZMje","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=pR7mTi6M","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=2eXfIe25","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=x6TUbV7a"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=sz-jyUye","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=1jg7ZNkA","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=VEBhU4QG","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=pSPPYdnq","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=bEc-aHdv"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=tfPYWcqI","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=x__RaAM6","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=3cQ0Jlgn","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=LpMOzfUW","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=_BpDUpt9"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=NOtA60WM","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=jY5ySjns","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=XKjS2eY_","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=gGXtqfc_","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=V-_Az0ZM"}}},"teaser_body":"The transition from an interim administration will likely restore political stability, though social and fiscal pressures will still pose constraints for the new center-right government.","pov":"","mailout":"The Bangladesh Nationalist Party's election victory will strengthen political stability, while its legislative supermajority will enable the party to advance constitutional and economic reforms and pursue a foreign policy that balances ties with India and China; however, social and fiscal pressures will constrain its efforts to reform the country in the wake of the 2024 revolution. On Feb. 13, the center-right Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) announced that it won Bangladesh's Feb. 12 parliamentary elections, positioning its leader, Tarique Rahman, the son of the late former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia, to assume the premiership. As of Feb. 13, the Election Commission had not yet published the official results, but several local media outlets report that the party surpassed the 151-seat threshold needed for a simple majority in the 350-member parliament, winning an estimated 209 general seats that, when combined with seats allocated after results are confirmed, give the BNP a two-thirds supermajority. The other main contender was an Islamist party, Jamaat-e-Islami, which participated as part of an 11-party alliance that cumulatively only won an estimated 74 seats. Once the Election Commission publishes the official gazette, newly elected members of parliament are required to take their oaths within three days, formally transferring power from an interim government that has led the country for the past year and a half and enabling the formation of the new government. Alongside the parliamentary vote, Bangladeshis also approved a referendum on the interim government's proposed constitutional reforms. While this carries significant political weight and will pressure lawmakers to enact the reforms, the outcome is legally non-binding and still requires parliamentary approval to take effect.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1771019311","created_formatted":"Feb 13, 2026 | 21:48 GMT","changed":"1771019311","changed_formatted":"Feb 13, 2026 | 21:48 GMT","path_alias":"article/bangladesh-nationalist-party-wins-big-first-election-2024-uprising","article_type":{"tid":"502","vid":"30","name":"Assessments"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"116","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Bangladesh","code":"BD","path_alias":"/region/south-asia/bangladesh"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"116","vid":"5","name":"Bangladesh"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"290404","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Geopolitical Calendar","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Geopolitical Calendar Display 02212025 (1).png","alt":"","title":"","caption":"","credit":"","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=T9P3aalD","small":"16x9_small/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=5LXK3mLR","medium":"16x9_medium/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=-Kapc68c","large":"16x9_large/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=Mjo-ZT4S","full":"16x9_full/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=ohIFDc-Q"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=G5oZsqCF","small":"square_small/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=hsp0opFR","medium":"square_medium/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=lnqDbWT6","large":"square_large/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=voxtoV-v","full":"square_full/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=wfqx8zOx"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=GMIRiQ2c","small":"article_small/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=7sDSOw7o","medium":"article_medium/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=XvKVYFUS","large":"article_large/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=h_kiwHxw","full":"article_full/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=eaMGMb4J"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=mEb6tgej","small":"2x1_small/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=WIvx21Qt","medium":"2x1_medium/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=5Rw5hFvn","large":"2x1_large/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=3EaGWqB5","full":"2x1_full/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=T_k0z6re"}}},"teaser_body":"Stay informed about the significant meetings and events RANE analysts are tracking.","pov":"","mailout":"Stay informed about the significant meetings and events RANE analysts are tracking.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1771014134","created_formatted":"Feb 13, 2026 | 20:22 GMT","changed":"1771014134","changed_formatted":"Feb 13, 2026 | 20:22 GMT","path_alias":"article/geopolitical-calendar","article_type":{"tid":"502","vid":"30","name":"Assessments"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"352002","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"The Strategic Risks of Europe's Pivot to U.S. LNG","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2247701286.jpg","alt":"The U.S. and the EU flags are seen side by side on Nov. 21, 2025, in Brussels, Belgium. ","title":"The U.S. and the EU flags are seen side by side on Nov. 21, 2025, in Brussels, Belgium. ","caption":"The U.S. and the EU flags are seen side by side on Nov. 21, 2025, in Brussels, Belgium.","credit":"(Thierry Monasse/Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=ZpQbGgOO","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=a-ofPpQV","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=349WVSDP","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=cHbEPVG7","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=zT6CaQff"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=cCTqAJhV","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=6nC3d0u6","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=vphNwoKT","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=9f6i6CrA","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=VL6La5yM"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=28HTTvXF","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=UWqKqgbH","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=87GO1Y-f","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=YVCvfoJH","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=09kwAR8G"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=9ZezKyP6","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=JqWWQMa1","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=njDZZ8-7","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=Lc8AP3IP","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2247701286.jpg?itok=PllSngwr"}}},"teaser_body":"By replacing Russian gas with U.S. LNG, the EU risks becoming reliant on another systemically central external supplier at a time of growing geopolitical instability and transatlantic tension.","pov":"","mailout":"By replacing Russian gas with U.S. LNG, the European Union risks swapping a strategic dependence on Moscow for one on Washington -- a relationship that, though fundamentally different, would not be immune to the use of energy as a tool of political and economic leverage, and that could leave the bloc operating with tighter market buffers and greater price volatility through the end of the decade, even as diversification reduces single-supplier risk. On Jan. 26, EU energy ministers approved legislation to phase out imports of Russian pipeline gas and liquefied natural gas (LNG) by the end of 2027. The phased ban will begin taking effect six weeks after it enters into force and tighten progressively through 2027, requiring companies to unwind existing agreements within defined timelines or face financial penalties. Spot imports of Russian gas and LNG will be prohibited six weeks after publication. Russian LNG imports under short-term contracts concluded before June 2025 will be banned from April 2026, while imports under long-term LNG contracts will be banned from January 2027. Pipeline gas imports under short-term contracts concluded before June 2025 will also be banned from June 2026, while imports under long-term contracts will be phased out from September 2027, with extensions possible until November 2027 if EU member states are not on track to meet gas storage targets. Russian oil imports are not covered under the approved package, though the European Commission has indicated it plans to submit additional legislation later this year to also prohibit Russian oil imports by the end of 2027.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770931237","created_formatted":"Feb 12, 2026 | 21:20 GMT","changed":"1770931341","changed_formatted":"Feb 12, 2026 | 21:22 GMT","path_alias":"article/strategic-risks-europes-pivot-us-lng","article_type":{"tid":"502","vid":"30","name":"Assessments"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United States","code":"US","path_alias":"/region/americas/united-states"},{"tid":"21","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Europe","code":"","path_alias":"/region/europe"},{"tid":"526","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Energy","path_alias":"/topic/energy"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","name":"United States"},{"tid":"21","vid":"5","name":"Europe"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"526","vid":"33","name":"Energy"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351972","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Economic Concessions to U.S. Offer Path for Regime Survival in Cuba","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2260228972.jpg","alt":"American Airlines planes sit on the tarmac at Jose Marti International Airport in Havana on Feb. 9, 2026. ","title":"American Airlines planes sit on the tarmac at Jose Marti International Airport in Havana on Feb. 9, 2026. ","caption":"American Airlines planes sit on the tarmac at Jose Marti International Airport in Havana on Feb. 9, 2026. ","credit":"(YAMIL LAGE/AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=-jmoWiDX","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=5353kHUl","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=2gja2f6S","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=Li0IgqY-","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=so9AwDdc"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=MoWCH8yR","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=oOeQQqaP","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=SWdj_kqQ","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=_Iuw4E5g","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=5_sd8lXR"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=aOgmjH_l","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=ykVI-RHl","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=aIgO_PTk","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=uhZIpEWl","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=1Oqfi0n-"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=G_aE7MGI","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=lHSgB0gs","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=k0elTWVc","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=5fHCHHd8","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2260228972.jpg?itok=pLyr6qVF"}}},"teaser_body":"Facing imminent economic collapse and the loss of key allies, the Cuban government will likely yield to U.S. demands for market liberalization to avoid a total breakdown of state authority while attempting to preserve political control.","pov":"","mailout":"Facing imminent collapse and mounting U.S. pressure, the Cuban government will likely make concessions to Washington to gradually open its economy without requiring structural political changes, which the United States will likely support to avoid a state collapse and reaffirm its geopolitical dominance in the Western Hemisphere.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770749346","created_formatted":"Feb 10, 2026 | 18:49 GMT","changed":"1770826465","changed_formatted":"Feb 11, 2026 | 16:14 GMT","path_alias":"article/economic-concessions-us-offer-path-regime-survival-cuba","article_type":{"tid":"502","vid":"30","name":"Assessments"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"39","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Cuba","code":"CU","path_alias":"/region/americas/cuba"},{"tid":"49","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Mexico","code":"MX","path_alias":"/region/americas/mexico"},{"tid":"59","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United States","code":"US","path_alias":"/region/americas/united-states"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"526","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Energy","path_alias":"/topic/energy"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"39","vid":"5","name":"Cuba"},{"tid":"49","vid":"5","name":"Mexico"},{"tid":"59","vid":"5","name":"United States"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"526","vid":"33","name":"Energy"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351939","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"The Weekly Rundown: Japan Holds Snap Elections, U.S. Weighs Options After Iran Talks","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2259572154.jpg","alt":"Campaign posters Feb. 6 of candidates running in the upcoming Japanese House of Representatives election, in Inagi, Tokyo prefecture.","title":"Campaign posters Feb. 6 of candidates running in the upcoming Japanese House of Representatives election, in Inagi, Tokyo prefecture.","caption":"Campaign posters Feb. 6 of candidates running in the upcoming Japanese House of Representatives election, in Inagi, Tokyo prefecture.","credit":"(Yuichi YAMAZAKI/AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=ZXSZ5wo2","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=F0Ru79YU","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=D6U8ewu9","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=ZvRkuh42","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=DY8ST9TU"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=WeZzGMyB","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=wFa_swX-","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=u3ZGAEXS","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=jAKXjIfT","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=M__qwY5V"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=VgytrZAT","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=sLoXacxF","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=m7SO6im5","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=Q1MPaGC_","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=Bk-gjJFL"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=Jq_kEV9E","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=DFdpAqb0","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=thklhx_T","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=i9QLrx93","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2259572154.jpg?itok=IJSI6Yc5"}}},"teaser_body":"A look at what the coming week will bring -- and a list of recommended RANE articles from the week that was.","pov":"","mailout":"A look at what the coming week will bring -- and a list of recommended RANE articles from the week that was.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770472800","created_formatted":"Feb 7, 2026 | 14:00 GMT","changed":"1770472827","changed_formatted":"Feb 7, 2026 | 14:00 GMT","path_alias":"article/weekly-rundown-japan-holds-snap-elections-us-weighs-options-after-iran-talks","article_type":{"tid":"502","vid":"30","name":"Assessments"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United States","code":"US","path_alias":"/region/americas/united-states"},{"tid":"125","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Iran","code":"IR","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa/iran"},{"tid":"200","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Japan","code":"JP","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/japan"},{"tid":"217","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Thailand","code":"TH","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/thailand"},{"tid":"116","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Bangladesh","code":"BD","path_alias":"/region/south-asia/bangladesh"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","name":"United States"},{"tid":"125","vid":"5","name":"Iran"},{"tid":"200","vid":"5","name":"Japan"},{"tid":"217","vid":"5","name":"Thailand"},{"tid":"116","vid":"5","name":"Bangladesh"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"},{"tid":"1660","vid":"33","name":"U.S.-Iran Relations"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351936","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Lessons Learned From Indonesia's Market Rout","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2258212948 (1).jpg","alt":"Visitors take pictures in front of an electronic board displaying falling stock prices at the Indonesia Stock Exchange in Jakarta on Jan. 29, 2026.","title":"Visitors take pictures in front of an electronic board displaying falling stock prices at the Indonesia Stock Exchange in Jakarta on Jan. 29, 2026.","caption":"Visitors take pictures in front of an electronic board displaying falling stock prices at the Indonesia Stock Exchange in Jakarta on Jan. 29, 2026.","credit":"(YASUYOSHI CHIBA / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=paonbKCG","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=HZXNR7N2","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=12Gl42M7","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=MkzNtyoC","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=xhVFtvCw"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=27dRLCmW","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=5gTXsTu_","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=734pUUqt","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=7fw3unKh","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=r5NP-X6Z"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=CZ-ArUvP","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=3Oyyd-Xi","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=qCor6Hs9","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=qoVCixbi","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=xXau38a4"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=VffYvvQ_","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=8_ee7EGO","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=QuFQx3a4","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=3FJ3Mm0f","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2258212948%20%281%29.jpg?itok=1MoQyNQE"}}},"teaser_body":"The episode exposes structural risks embedded in the president's governance that could threaten investor confidence -- and with it, Indonesia's economic growth and manufacturing competitiveness.","pov":"","mailout":"Indonesia's market rout has exposed deeper structural and governance vulnerabilities that now threaten investor confidence, complicate the government's investment-led growth strategy and raise risks to the country's competitiveness as a regional manufacturing hub. On Jan. 29, Indonesia's equity market sold off sharply after MSCI, a U.S.-based global index provider, raised concerns about the \"investability\" of Indonesian equities. MSCI cited opaque ownership structures, a small proportion of shares available for public trading and insufficient transparency around trading and shareholder data, and warned that Indonesia's equity market could be downgraded from \"emerging market\" to \"frontier market\" status if deficiencies were not addressed ahead of MSCI's scheduled May index review. Following the warning, the benchmark Jakarta Composite Index fell more than 8% over two consecutive trading days, including a steep intraday decline on Jan. 30 that triggered an automatic trading halt under exchange volatility rules. The selloff wiped out an estimated $80 billion in market capitalization before prices stabilized later in the day, following public statements and press briefings by the Ministry of Finance, Bank Indonesia, the Financial Services Authority and the Indonesia Stock Exchange outlining prospective regulatory and market support measures. At the same time, financial stress spilled into currency markets, causing the Indonesian rupiah to weaken by approximately 4%; the currency traded near record lows before stabilizing. The episode escalated further on Feb. 5 when Moody's Ratings cut Indonesia's sovereign credit rating outlook from \"stable\" to \"negative,\" citing lower policy predictability, rising fiscal pressures, weakening foreign reserves and debt risks linked to state-owned enterprises, broadening the episode from an equity market shock into an explicit warning about sovereign policy credibility. The market selloff was followed by significant leadership changes at key financial institutions. On Jan. 30, the head of Indonesia's financial regulator, several senior officials overseeing capital markets and the chief executive of the stock exchange all resigned. The sudden departures have fueled fears that less independent individuals will fill these leadership positions, potentially opening these key market institutions to greater influence by the president, even as authorities sought to reassure investors that day-to-day market operations would continue without disruption. Since the selloff, markets have stabilized but not recovered.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770401479","created_formatted":"Feb 6, 2026 | 18:11 GMT","changed":"1770401479","changed_formatted":"Feb 6, 2026 | 18:11 GMT","path_alias":"article/lessons-learned-indonesias-market-rout","article_type":{"tid":"502","vid":"30","name":"Assessments"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"199","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Indonesia","code":"ID","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/indonesia"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"199","vid":"5","name":"Indonesia"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351926","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Elections and Referendum Unlikely to End Thailand's Cycle of Constrained Governance","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2258988687.jpg","alt":"People walk past campaign posters in Bangkok on Feb. 2, 2026, ahead of Thailand's Feb. 8 general election.","title":"People walk past campaign posters in Bangkok on Feb. 2, 2026, ahead of Thailand's Feb. 8 general election.","caption":"People walk past campaign posters in Bangkok on Feb. 2, 2026, ahead of Thailand's Feb. 8 general election.","credit":"(Lillian SUWANRUMPHA / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=2QLQPCvP","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=HicGBYVA","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=Jp_z8-hc","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=x8tak_UZ","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=Ju0ZxwDn"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=OmchwBDH","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=h-0K_Pq0","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=T24RqxH4","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=ymI8CG3r","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=_z2YBesY"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=MHYpdB79","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=IfVJZ2wG","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=4lfcRruR","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=2bnZcsfd","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=Zedojxoe"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=QCJZitgE","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=X1r-ohmS","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=CCpz4vRH","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=RcP9azdK","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2258988687.jpg?itok=NPDkpy9_"}}},"teaser_body":"Thailand's Feb. 8 general election and constitutional referendum are unlikely to deliver a decisive political reset and will instead risk extending a familiar cycle of constrained reform and policy caution amid heightened security and economic pressures.","pov":"","mailout":"Thailand's general election and constitutional referendum are unlikely to deliver a decisive political reset and will instead risk extending a familiar cycle of contested governance, constrained reform and policy caution amid heightened security pressures and economic underperformance. On Feb. 8, Thailand will hold a general election for the 500-seat House of Representatives and a national referendum on whether to initiate the drafting of a new constitution to replace the 2017 charter. Under Thailand's parallel voting system, 400 members of parliament will be elected from constituencies and 100 from party lists. Forming a government will require the support of at least 251 lawmakers to select a prime minister. The election is being contested primarily by three major political blocs: a progressive and reformist camp led by the People's Party, center-right forces aligned with the governing Bhumjaithai Party and the established political network of the center-left Pheu Thai Party, which advocates redistributive economic policies and welfare expansion. Key campaign issues include economic policy, governance and constitutional reforms, and national security issues following the large-scale cross-border clashes with Cambodia in 2025 and the subsequent failed ceasefires.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770323285","created_formatted":"Feb 5, 2026 | 20:28 GMT","changed":"1770323285","changed_formatted":"Feb 5, 2026 | 20:28 GMT","path_alias":"article/elections-and-referendum-unlikely-end-thailands-cycle-constrained-governance","article_type":{"tid":"502","vid":"30","name":"Assessments"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"217","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Thailand","code":"TH","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/thailand"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"217","vid":"5","name":"Thailand"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0}],"isLoadingData":false,"type":"filtered_content_feed"},{"template_id":"template13","title":"Snapshots","subqueue_id":"","filter":{"type":["article","sectioned_content"],"taxonomy":{"article_type":{"505":"505"},"assessments_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"column_type":[],"countries":[],"wv_themes":[],"wv_topics":[],"wv_series":[],"wv_event":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[]}},"limit":"8","page":0,"totalCount":20,"nodes":[{"nid":"352001","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Argentina's Milei Secures Senate Backing for Market-Oriented Labor Overhaul","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2260596032.jpg","alt":"An aerial photo shows Argentinian police using a water cannon truck against protesters opposing labor reforms on Feb. 11, 2026, in Buenos Aires, Argentina.","title":"An aerial photo shows Argentinian police using a water cannon truck against protesters opposing labor reforms on Feb. 11, 2026, in Buenos Aires, Argentina.","caption":"An aerial photo shows Argentinian police using a water cannon truck against protesters opposing labor reforms on Feb. 11, 2026, in Buenos Aires, Argentina.","credit":"(Tomas Cuesta/Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=40ysSrAa","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=hBCUbM7R","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=SFFj5hDG","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=LZ_lBnn1","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=vFA8nUkT"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=G0Pkduku","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=P5YpyQcR","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=ZTNq2yph","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=pWErCsa7","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=8yGJ13Sk"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=HMRRViVK","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=UXvlByUO","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=9eDoA8Pv","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=4N-sgbAj","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=1dk4ja7b"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=jjGbCAtl","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=1zmYLazv","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=3ot0I4VD","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=rvprIPKm","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2260596032.jpg?itok=_UABuasP"}}},"teaser_body":"Although the labor reform is likely to be approved and may incrementally improve Argentina's hiring climate, its short-term economic impact will be limited.","pov":"","mailout":"The likely approval of Argentina's labor reform will improve hiring incentives over time and strengthen the government's broader market-oriented agenda, though the short-term economic impact will be limited by high labor costs and weak domestic demand. On Feb. 12, the Argentine Senate voted 42 to 30 with no abstentions to approve a landmark labor reform bill put forward by President Javier Milei's administration. The reform seeks to overhaul Argentina's labor law regime, much of which dates to the 1970s and has been characterized by rigid protections for workers and subject to heavy litigation. Key elements in the Senate text include reductions in severance obligations and a restructured approach to termination liabilities, more flexible working hours (which in some cases may allow workers to work for up to 12 hours), the extension of the probationary period for new workers from three to six months and an expansion of the list of services deemed \"essential\" (which reduces their right to go on strike). The reform also offers reduced penalties for companies with off-the-books workers who decide to formalize them. After Senate approval, the bill will proceed to the Chamber of Deputies for final consideration. A vote in the lower house is expected in late February or early March.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770919815","created_formatted":"Feb 12, 2026 | 18:10 GMT","changed":"1770919815","changed_formatted":"Feb 12, 2026 | 18:10 GMT","path_alias":"article/milei-secures-senate-backing-market-oriented-labor-overhaul","article_type":{"tid":"505","vid":"30","name":"Snapshots"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"30","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Argentina","code":"AR","path_alias":"/region/americas/argentina"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"30","vid":"5","name":"Argentina"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351996","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Thailand Approves Constitutional Reform, Re-Elects Conservative Party","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2260130838.jpg","alt":"Thai Prime Minister Anutin Charnvirakul arrives at the Government House in Bangkok on Feb. 9, 2026.","title":"Thai Prime Minister Anutin Charnvirakul arrives at the Government House in Bangkok on Feb. 9, 2026.","caption":"Thai Prime Minister Anutin Charnvirakul arrives at the Government House in Bangkok on Feb. 9, 2026.","credit":"(chanakarn laosarakham / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=1waK-tmN","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=6I9LVGHQ","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=O6HTuhP-","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=NI8uKQVt","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=houasVpf"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=ysJljMoO","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=c4Obp89Q","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=YjOoXXcF","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=7HF9tW74","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=d0BFqJ6X"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=aeLcrg9G","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=nRnn3tWU","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=o5LtlPue","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=0d-BvNvc","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=SGNG9bmW"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=5YVTWU6u","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=BuEE7HHK","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=JQEabTpj","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=9etclAM5","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2260130838.jpg?itok=ru2-gYny"}}},"teaser_body":"The incumbent conservative party's victory will improve short-term political stability, but governance will remain constrained by coalition dynamics, entrenched institutions and uncertain constitutional reform.","pov":"","mailout":"In Thailand, an electoral win for the incumbent conservative party will improve short-term political stability, but coalition politics, the power of entrenched institutions and uncertainty over the trajectory of constitutional reform will continue to constrain governance and sustain political risk. On Feb. 8, Thai Prime Minister Anutin Charnvirakul's center-right Bhumjaithai Party won a decisive plurality in snap general elections. With roughly 95% of votes counted as of Feb. 11, Bhumjaithai was projected to win about 193 of 500 seats, well short of an outright majority but far ahead of the progressive opposition People's Party, which won roughly 118 seats, and the center-left Pheu Thai Party, which won roughly 74 seats. Coalition talks began immediately, with the People's Party publicly ruling out participation in an Anutin-led coalition, while Anutin emphasized the need for a robust majority and pledged tougher border measures and a stronger military posture. The result was widely interpreted as a consolidation of the conservative vote around Anutin's campaign emphasis on border security, military readiness and national stability following the reemergence of border conflict with Cambodia in 2025, while the People's Party significantly underperformed relative to pre-election polls. In parallel, nearly two-thirds of voters approved a constitutional referendum to begin the process of replacing the 2017 charter. The vote authorizes initiating a drafting pathway but does not itself produce a new constitutional text. Meanwhile, the post-vote political environment also shifted quickly against the reformist bloc. On Feb. 9, Thailand's National Anti-Corruption Commission announced findings that 44 former lawmakers from the former Move Forward Party (the People's Party's banned predecessor), including 10 who won seats in the Feb. 8 polls, breached ethical standards over a past push to amend Thailand's royal defamation law, with the matter to be forwarded to the Supreme Court, whose decision could could affect parliamentary arithmetic if judges suspend or ban the candidates from office.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770849866","created_formatted":"Feb 11, 2026 | 22:44 GMT","changed":"1770849866","changed_formatted":"Feb 11, 2026 | 22:44 GMT","path_alias":"article/thailand-approves-constitutional-reform-re-elects-conservative-party","article_type":{"tid":"505","vid":"30","name":"Snapshots"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"217","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Thailand","code":"TH","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/thailand"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"217","vid":"5","name":"Thailand"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351979","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"In the U.K., Starmer's Leadership Struggles Reach a Tipping Point","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2259578301.jpg","alt":"U.K. Prime Minister Keir Starmer leaves Downing Street on Feb. 2, 2026, in London. ","title":"U.K. Prime Minister Keir Starmer leaves Downing Street on Feb. 2, 2026, in London. ","caption":"U.K. Prime Minister Keir Starmer leaves Downing Street on Feb. 2, 2026, in London.","credit":"(Alishia Abodunde/Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=S3NZEFfF","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=ZkDhmsZJ","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=hqXPZ48L","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=pWoKEHD8","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=nyhphrUX"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=aURTbgcL","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=l_J1KnaB","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=c_aptKxN","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=Hfs-G8XF","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=sf_KHi9E"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=IEP_4tmN","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=7IsR6WKq","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=I75hhyQU","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=d_VjyVeY","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=CurFH1A4"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=FmRst5W9","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=EtkeCFDP","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=6iepaXAP","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=sMrk64YZ","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2259578301.jpg?itok=tBn3s-Ci"}}},"teaser_body":"While the crisis could see Labour elect a new leader in the coming months, broad party consensus and fiscal constraints make sharp policy shifts unlikely, limiting the risk of sustained market volatility.","pov":"","mailout":"A deepening internal crisis within Labour is weakening Prime Minister Keir Starmer's authority and raising the likelihood of a leadership challenge, but structural constraints and broad party consensus make sharp policy shifts or a break with the United Kingdom's current fiscal trajectory unlikely, limiting the risk to only limited, short-term market volatility. Starmer's leadership came under acute pressure after renewed controversy over his appointment of Peter Mandelson as ambassador to the United States triggered senior resignations in Downing Street and open calls for him to step aside. Chief of staff Morgan McSweeney resigned on Feb. 8, taking responsibility for advising Starmer on the appointment despite Mandelson's past association with convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein. Tim Allan, Starmer's director of communications, followed suit shortly thereafter. Officials cited by British media said cabinet ministers were also preparing to privately urge Starmer to resign or threaten their own departures. On Feb. 9, Scottish Labour leader Anas Sarwar publicly called for Starmer's resignation, becoming the most senior Labour figure to do so. At least for now, however, Starmer maintains the public support of senior government members, including those U.K. media have identified as potential contenders for Labour Party leadership, such as Former Deputy Prime Minister Angela Rayner, Health Secretary Wes Streeting, Home Secretary Shabana Mahmood and Energy Secretary Ed Miliband.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770752187","created_formatted":"Feb 10, 2026 | 19:36 GMT","changed":"1770752306","changed_formatted":"Feb 10, 2026 | 19:38 GMT","path_alias":"article/uk-starmers-leadership-struggles-reach-tipping-point","article_type":{"tid":"505","vid":"30","name":"Snapshots"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"102","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United Kingdom","code":"GB","path_alias":"/region/europe/united-kingdom"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"102","vid":"5","name":"United Kingdom"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351968","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Election Landslide Stabilizes Japanese Politics, Cements Defense Modernization","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2259987841.jpg","alt":"Japanese Prime Minister and President of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) Sanae Takaichi reacts as she speaks with media on the day of lower house elections at the LDP headquarters in Tokyo on Feb. 8, 2026. ","title":"Japanese Prime Minister and President of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) Sanae Takaichi reacts as she speaks with media on the day of lower house elections at the LDP headquarters in Tokyo on Feb. 8, 2026. ","caption":"Japanese Prime Minister and President of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) Sanae Takaichi reacts as she speaks with media on the day of lower house elections at the LDP headquarters in Tokyo on Feb. 8, 2026.","credit":"(Kim Kyung-Hoon / POOL / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=y-L9LnM1","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=mAo7WYNu","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=tRRQojaz","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=opyMYmJ2","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=I7p-D2Qe"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=I1aZSLR9","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=A4F5ut0i","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=07fwFraz","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=wqAXeEm1","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=bicXIZC1"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=rv6UY8vu","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=c-KjrKL6","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=dlPftPmK","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=2WFgd2LC","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=2BHBkOKC"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=4hfCDB6u","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=f3Vz0Kyf","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=F3fy19tC","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=u8hLEU0B","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2259987841.jpg?itok=RZySD0-g"}}},"teaser_body":"The LDP's decisive lower house victory will enable Prime Minister Takaichi to boost social and defense spending and strengthen ties with the U.S., though at the expense of Japan’s relations with China and South Korea.","pov":"","mailout":"A major electoral victory by Japan's ruling party will enable conservative Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi to expand social and defense spending, ease lingering concerns about political instability and bolster ties with the United States, though at the expense of those with China and potentially South Korea. Takaichi's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) won 316 out of 465 seats in the Feb. 8 snap elections for the lower house of the Diet, giving it a rare supermajority and the largest seat share in its party history. When combined with its coalition partner, the Japan Innovation Party, the LDP-led government now has 352 seats. Opposition parties, on the other hand, heavily underperformed. The main opposition Centrist Reform Alliance (CRA) -- formed in recent weeks by a merger of the center-left Constitutional Democratic Party and former LDP coalition partner, the center-left Komeito -- saw its seat count drop from 167 to just 49. Other opposition parties across the political spectrum also generally underperformed, with the exception of the right-wing nativist party Sanseito, which rose from two to 15 seats. The Diet will convene a special session on Feb. 18 to vote on the next prime minister, which Takaichi is guaranteed to win. The session will also hand control of the powerful lower house standing committees to the LDP and belatedly commence work on the 2026 budget, which is due by March 31.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770676588","created_formatted":"Feb 9, 2026 | 22:36 GMT","changed":"1770676588","changed_formatted":"Feb 9, 2026 | 22:36 GMT","path_alias":"article/election-landslide-stabilizes-japanese-politics-cements-defense-modernization","article_type":{"tid":"505","vid":"30","name":"Snapshots"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"200","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Japan","code":"JP","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/japan"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"200","vid":"5","name":"Japan"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351958","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"In Tunisia, UGTT Infighting Risks Playing Into President Saied's Hands","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2230479411.jpg","alt":"Supporters of Tunisia's General Labour Union (UGTT) wave the national flag during a rally in Tunis on Aug. 21, 2025.","title":"Supporters of Tunisia's General Labour Union (UGTT) wave the national flag during a rally in Tunis on Aug. 21, 2025.","caption":"Supporters of Tunisia's General Labour Union (UGTT) wave the national flag during a rally in Tunis on Aug. 21, 2025.","credit":"(FETHI BELAID/AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=7Q6OnFaI","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=zZ5mgjsU","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=sIX6jTBC","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=ZrYuLuL7","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=ikeg2Xw6"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=_YjxNxQ1","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=9VmsttyC","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=SbU5LHSe","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=nMqRLtK9","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=kWqdEfGc"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=Rbuvv2V2","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=uJQc_3XU","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=pIokp_9r","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=aIORQCU_","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=uGxCiXvq"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=CjKjlwEv","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=kwVLxLf5","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=W5YOeM2f","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=9lViFEbT","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2230479411.jpg?itok=NH-EsFKW"}}},"teaser_body":"If the UGTT fails to resolve internal disputes and stage an effective national strike, President Saied will likely launch an expanded crackdown that further weakens the powerful labor union and, consequently, its private-sector bargaining power.","pov":"","mailout":"In Tunisia, officials from the country's influential labor union confederation will likely try to mend internal disputes to increase the effectiveness of any rescheduled national strike, but failure to do so would likely embolden Tunisian President Kais Saied to further erode the union's strength and, in turn, private-sector bargaining power. Nearly three weeks have passed since the Tunisian General Labor Union, or UGTT, had originally intended to conduct a nationwide general strike on Jan. 21. On Jan. 23, the union's deputy secretary-general suggested that a decision regarding the future of the strike would be determined at the union's congress, tentatively scheduled for March 25-27. Union leadership originally called for the strike in December 2025 to protest the Tunisian government's crackdown on the opposition, protect the union's right to collective bargaining after the central government sidelined the union from wage and pension increase negotiations, and call for dialogue between government and union leaders. The decision to postpone the strike came amid internal disputes and uncertainty over union leadership following several officials' resignations. Most notably, Nourreddine Taboubi, the secretary-general, submitted his resignation on Dec. 23 but later withdrew it on Jan. 13, in what some critics alleged was a calculated move to pressure union leaders ahead of the legal deadline to call off a strike. Taboubi's resignation elevated concerns among union officials that the change in leadership -- particularly ahead of a planned nationwide strike -- risked deeper fragmentation and could fuel internal divisions.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770665104","created_formatted":"Feb 9, 2026 | 19:25 GMT","changed":"1770665104","changed_formatted":"Feb 9, 2026 | 19:25 GMT","path_alias":"article/tunisia-ugtt-infighting-risks-playing-president-saieds-hands","article_type":{"tid":"505","vid":"30","name":"Snapshots"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"188","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Tunisia","code":"TN","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa/tunisia"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"188","vid":"5","name":"Tunisia"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351937","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"The Limits of Russia-Ukraine-U.S. Talks","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2259311376.jpg","alt":"Emirati flags on Feb. 4 in Abu Dhabi, UAE.","title":"Emirati flags on Feb. 4 in Abu Dhabi, UAE. On Feb. 4-5, delegations from Russia, Ukraine and the United States held a second round of trilateral talks in the United Arab Emirates.","caption":"Emirati flags on Feb. 4 in Abu Dhabi, UAE.","credit":"(CACACE/AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=O0990CCQ","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=9AMR0gC5","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=yhu7l95X","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=ZnsU-lcL","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=ueRSUL_5"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=7xKZLKtf","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=3Bs9Ppi5","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=8Xs9NrbC","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=OjskrbN0","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=ToLUs0Kg"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=XnWu9E1h","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=QqNAGeHk","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=sCEeJN7D","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=m5hGFbhZ","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=bNuY0NZZ"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=PoBSNoVW","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=GmlJYJrA","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=cTl2fS1W","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=0vo3Ikn-","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2259311376.jpg?itok=4Xe_rnz9"}}},"teaser_body":"The talks are unlikely to produce a near-term settlement, as Russia will continue to press its territorial demands while using diplomacy to manage sanctions pressure and build leverage ahead of a spring-summer offensive.","pov":"","mailout":"U.S.-brokered talks between Russia and Ukraine will likely continue, and to deliver limited confidence-building steps. But they are unlikely to produce a near-term settlement, as Russia will continue to press its territorial demands while using diplomacy to manage sanctions pressure and build leverage ahead of a spring-summer offensive.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770405545","created_formatted":"Feb 6, 2026 | 19:19 GMT","changed":"1770406072","changed_formatted":"Feb 6, 2026 | 19:27 GMT","path_alias":"article/limits-russia-ukraine-us-talks","article_type":{"tid":"505","vid":"30","name":"Snapshots"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United States","code":"US","path_alias":"/region/americas/united-states"},{"tid":"138","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United Arab Emirates","code":"AE","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa/united-arab-emirates"},{"tid":"113","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Ukraine","code":"UA","path_alias":"/region/eurasia/ukraine"},{"tid":"110","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Russia","code":"RU","path_alias":"/region/eurasia/russia"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"},{"tid":"1840","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Russia-Ukraine Conflict","path_alias":"/topic/russia-ukraine-conflict"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","name":"United States"},{"tid":"138","vid":"5","name":"United Arab Emirates"},{"tid":"113","vid":"5","name":"Ukraine"},{"tid":"110","vid":"5","name":"Russia"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"},{"tid":"1840","vid":"33","name":"Russia-Ukraine Conflict"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351908","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Understanding the EU's Strategic Reengagement With Turkey","promo_image":{"uri":"public://EU Turkey GettyImages-2152850120.jpg","alt":"A digital satellite illustration shows Europe at night.","title":"A digital satellite illustration shows Europe at night.","caption":"A digital illustration shows a lit-up map of Europe.","credit":"(Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=KeTrBeG3","small":"16x9_small/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=lVCXl6r6","medium":"16x9_medium/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=hL8zDpRv","large":"16x9_large/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=-R2se54_","full":"16x9_full/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=x_dHdWnj"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=Zx-HbaPm","small":"square_small/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=-cGxMB4-","medium":"square_medium/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=JmprHWO7","large":"square_large/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=r2MMflIO","full":"square_full/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=Kc1YsyNj"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=UNQWRnXo","small":"article_small/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=rwtyPsh2","medium":"article_medium/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=OQgAm1mi","large":"article_large/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=7y4M4Amu","full":"article_full/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=lHlIltNa"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=0sZdxSgq","small":"2x1_small/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=jWgInv4_","medium":"2x1_medium/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=G2aR2Win","large":"2x1_large/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=f_sWYvC9","full":"2x1_full/public/EU%20Turkey%20GettyImages-2152850120.jpg?itok=nslJoV9e"}}},"teaser_body":"The EU enlargement chief's upcoming visit to Turkey signals an attempt to balance cautious engagement with clear strategic interests, rather than an imminent breakthrough on the country's stalled accession process.","pov":"","mailout":"The European Union's ongoing engagement with Turkey reflects a push toward pragmatic strategic re-engagement while managing -- rather than resolving -- the stalled accession process and enduring political frictions. European Commissioner for Enlargement Marta Kos will conduct an official visit to Turkey on Feb. 5-6. In a media interview ahead of the trip, Kos emphasized the need to \"look with fresh eyes\" at EU-Turkey relations, underscoring the mutual benefits of a stronger strategic partnership and the importance of building trust between the two sides amid global geopolitical shifts. During this visit, she will hold high-level meetings with Turkish counterparts across ministries, including foreign affairs, transport and infrastructure, energy and natural resources, and finance. She will also oversee the signing of at least two European Investment Bank-backed renewable energy projects, each valued at 100 million euros. Kos's agenda also includes discussions on trade, migration, connectivity strategy and mechanisms for enhancing people-to-people ties, such as visa liberalization.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770228563","created_formatted":"Feb 4, 2026 | 18:09 GMT","changed":"1770412119","changed_formatted":"Feb 6, 2026 | 21:08 GMT","path_alias":"article/understanding-eus-strategic-re-engagement-turkey","article_type":{"tid":"505","vid":"30","name":"Snapshots"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"137","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Turkey","code":"TR","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa/turkey"},{"tid":"21","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Europe","code":"","path_alias":"/region/europe"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"526","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Energy","path_alias":"/topic/energy"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"137","vid":"5","name":"Turkey"},{"tid":"21","vid":"5","name":"Europe"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"526","vid":"33","name":"Energy"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351902","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"An India-U.S. Trade Deal Will Face Ongoing Hurdles","promo_image":{"uri":"public://India Containers GettyImages-2231432670.jpg","alt":"A freight train on Aug. 26, 2025, in Ajmer India.","title":"A freight train on Aug. 26, 2025, in Ajmer India.","caption":"A freight train on Aug. 26, 2025, in Ajmer India.","credit":"(HIMANSHU SHARMA/AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=BPK1HPsj","small":"16x9_small/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=ZCT0UMn0","medium":"16x9_medium/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=vbWNUg9z","large":"16x9_large/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=xIww3YQB","full":"16x9_full/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=eCg2rzrB"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=H5rQVhMA","small":"square_small/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=XhH_jm6r","medium":"square_medium/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=-F1Zo9gN","large":"square_large/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=hAReoPQH","full":"square_full/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=B30ZZkC7"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=VQc7buOF","small":"article_small/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=PMqoJI5h","medium":"article_medium/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=6VPtcqHs","large":"article_large/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=Iq1D4TaI","full":"article_full/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=kscPQQhK"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=_CCesDDc","small":"2x1_small/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=bev88uZ6","medium":"2x1_medium/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=0wBX4yOm","large":"2x1_large/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=ibxJas1J","full":"2x1_full/public/India%20Containers%20GettyImages-2231432670.jpg?itok=xmPH0XtS"}}},"teaser_body":"A U.S.-India trade deal will bring some relief to Indian exporters, but ambiguities over its scope, implementation timeline and myriad other flashpoints will risk undermining it.","pov":"","mailout":"While a U.S.-India trade deal will bring some relief to Indian exporters, ambiguities over its scope, implementation timeline and myriad other flashpoints will keep the prospect of renewed U.S. tariffs and other coercive measures that undermine the deal on the table.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1770155121","created_formatted":"Feb 3, 2026 | 21:45 GMT","changed":"1770155815","changed_formatted":"Feb 3, 2026 | 21:56 GMT","path_alias":"article/india-us-trade-deal-will-face-ongoing-hurdles","article_type":{"tid":"505","vid":"30","name":"Snapshots"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United States","code":"US","path_alias":"/region/americas/united-states"},{"tid":"118","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"India","code":"IN","path_alias":"/region/south-asia/india"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","name":"United States"},{"tid":"118","vid":"5","name":"India"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0}],"isLoadingData":false,"type":"filtered_content_feed"},{"template_id":"template24","title":"Columns","subqueue_id":"","filter":{"type":["article","sectioned_content"],"taxonomy":{"article_type":[],"assessments_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"column_type":{"600":"600","601":"601","643":"643","644":"644"},"countries":[],"wv_themes":[],"wv_topics":[],"wv_series":[],"wv_event":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[]}},"limit":"8","page":0,"totalCount":20,"nodes":[{"nid":"352024","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"To Keep the Promise of Ukraine's Accession Alive, the EU Mulls Alternative Options","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2229852232.jpg","alt":"Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky attends a press conference at the European Commission's headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, on Aug. 17, 2025.","title":"Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky attends a press conference at the European Commission's headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, on Aug. 17, 2025.","caption":"Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky attends a press conference at the European Commission's headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, on Aug. 17, 2025.","credit":"(Simon Wohlfahrt / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=vL95hYtM","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=XPzpX9AR","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=lgTu6zyC","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=G7OjUNRZ","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=BSW3iCJd"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=qdQfyG7T","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=Osh5otOh","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=bOlnNHlg","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=6u9j3f9E","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=g8ADJeXQ"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=NXpJqtIq","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=px6ye8Oi","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=Wj8lvN8e","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=7gqBlA7G","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=gjlQaeAT"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=3YjsNb83","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=wNjEdoYG","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=CdM8A9Gn","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=i_28fL8F","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2229852232.jpg?itok=daPBwhQI"}}},"teaser_body":"Despite its strategic imperative to secure Ukraine's Western alignment, the EU remains unlikely to grant the country full or partial membership anytime soon due to numerous challenges, with the ongoing war being chief among them.","pov":"","mailout":"In recent months, several EU officials have said that the bloc is exploring ways to expedite Ukraine's accession, with some suggesting that Kyiv could join the European Union as early as 2027. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky has echoed this optimism, stating that Ukraine would be ready by then. Ukraine formally became an EU candidate in June 2022, shortly after Russia's full-scale invasion in February of that year. While EU accession is a lengthy and technically complex process (requiring compliance with extensive criteria grouped into six policy \"clusters\"), the European Commission stated in December 2025 that Ukraine had made significant progress across multiple areas. Still, with the war ongoing and Ukraine lagging on issues such as anti-corruption efforts and judicial reform, EU officials have increasingly argued that alternative pathways to membership should be explored. These include proposals for a phased or sequential accession, under which Ukraine would join the European Union in stages rather than through the current all-or-nothing framework. While these initiatives will enable closer EU-Ukraine cooperation in the coming years, the prospect of full, or even phased, membership will face numerous obstacles.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1771236000","created_formatted":"Feb 16, 2026 | 10:00 GMT","changed":"1771236027","changed_formatted":"Feb 16, 2026 | 10:00 GMT","path_alias":"article/keep-promise-ukraines-accession-alive-eu-mulls-alternative-options","article_type":{"tid":"506","vid":"30","name":"Columns"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"21","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Europe","code":"","path_alias":"/region/europe"},{"tid":"113","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Ukraine","code":"UA","path_alias":"/region/eurasia/ukraine"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"},{"tid":"1840","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Russia-Ukraine Conflict","path_alias":"/topic/russia-ukraine-conflict"}],"author":[{"nid":"211917","full_name":"Adriano Bosoni","first_name":"Adriano","last_name":"Bosoni","type_of_profile":[{"tid":"315","vid":"14","name":"Analyst"}],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"template_id":"","summary":"As Director of Analysis at RANE, Adriano Bosoni focuses on political, social and economic issues pertaining to the European Union and the eurozone.","biography":"\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003eAdriano Bosoni is Director of Analysis at RANE. His expertise is in European politics, economics and society, EU institutions and policies, risk analysis, demographics, migratory movements, and populism. He has more than a decade of experience forecasting geopolitical events on the Continent and has also worked on Latin American and Eurasian geopolitical forecasting. \u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eMr. Bosoni holds a journalism degree from USAL (Argentina), a master\u0026#39;s degree in International Relations from the University of Bologna (Italy), and has completed postgraduate courses on globalization (London School of Economics) and business analytics (Wharton, United States). He is also a former Fulbright scholar (University of Massachusetts Amherst).\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eMr. Bosoni is frequently featured in and cited by numerous newspapers and broadcasts from around the world. He has lived and worked in several countries in Europe and the Americas and is fluent in English, Spanish and Italian. You can follow him on Twitter at @AdrianoBosoni\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e","photo":"https://www.stratfor.com/sites/default/files/profiles/photos/Adriano-Bosoni.jpg","job_title":"Director of Analysis at RANE","organization":null,"organization_link":"","created":"1414773739","created_formatted":"Oct 31, 2014 | 16:42 GMT","changed":"1677513046","changed_formatted":"Feb 27, 2023 | 15:50 GMT","path_alias":"people/211917","status":1}],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"21","vid":"5","name":"Europe"},{"tid":"113","vid":"5","name":"Ukraine"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"},{"tid":"1840","vid":"33","name":"Russia-Ukraine Conflict"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351832","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"The Third Syrian State: Autocracy, Alignment and Al-Sharaa's Unique Neutrality","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Syria GettyImages-2249478635.jpg","alt":"A Syrian flag flutters above crowds gathering in central Hama, Syria, during celebrations on Dec. 5, 2025, marking one year since the fall of former President Bashar al Assad's regime.","title":"A Syrian flag flutters above crowds gathering in central Hama, Syria, during celebrations on Dec. 5, 2025, marking one year since the fall of former President Bashar al Assad's regime.","caption":"A Syrian flag flutters above crowds gathering in central Hama, Syria, during celebrations on Dec. 5, 2025, marking one year since the fall of former President Bashar al Assad's regime.","credit":"(OMAR HAJ KADOUR / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=Pv9_w1E6","small":"16x9_small/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=4bwiksbx","medium":"16x9_medium/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=pcW4ZRG4","large":"16x9_large/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=nFCwUUmv","full":"16x9_full/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=gDD2KcMZ"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=3_VTxon1","small":"square_small/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=4jmvZpL3","medium":"square_medium/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=iF-an-1H","large":"square_large/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=ZnkkT0ok","full":"square_full/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=X15tNVnk"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=JA02oCR2","small":"article_small/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=Q7wqGHya","medium":"article_medium/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=CpnzMBAu","large":"article_large/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=jNdeKibp","full":"article_full/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=ZOeOd-Km"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=r-eqcOg9","small":"2x1_small/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=HTQtWv4j","medium":"2x1_medium/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=LgGJt5fq","large":"2x1_large/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=MtKEaIn3","full":"2x1_full/public/Syria%20GettyImages-2249478635.jpg?itok=tG1YKuMa"}}},"teaser_body":"The third Syrian state, under interim President Ahmed al-Sharaa, will likely emerge as a Turkish-aligned, authoritarian regime that prioritizes internal stability, reconstruction and regional neutrality, as it tries to avoid its predecessors' mistakes and excesses.","pov":"","mailout":"More than a year after the fall of former President Bashar al Assad, the new Syria is still firming up its state identity -- and its place in the wider region. But the broader contours are now clear. There will be no Rojava, the decade-plus experiment in Kurdish self-rule that emerged in 2012, now that Syrian government forces, backed by Turkey and tolerated by the United States, have rolled over the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF). However, Syria will also not return to Assad-era repression, as the new government has offered Kurds significant language and cultural rights. Navigating domestic and foreign pressures, Syria is emerging as a Turkish-aligned, authoritarian state. For stability and reconstruction, it will maintain formal neutrality in the region's many conflicts, but Syria, struggling to escape Turkey's shadow and the Gulf Arabs' interests, will still inevitably be forced to endure some of those wars anyway.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1769640598","created_formatted":"Jan 28, 2026 | 22:49 GMT","changed":"1769640716","changed_formatted":"Jan 28, 2026 | 22:51 GMT","path_alias":"article/third-syrian-state-autocracy-alignment-and-al-sharaas-unique-neutrality","article_type":{"tid":"506","vid":"30","name":"Columns"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"136","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Syria","code":"SY","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa/syria"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[{"nid":"288686","full_name":"Ryan Bohl","first_name":"Ryan","last_name":"Bohl","type_of_profile":[{"tid":"315","vid":"14","name":"Analyst"}],"column_type":[],"template_id":"","summary":"","biography":"\u003cdiv\u003eRyan Bohl is a Senior Middle East and North Africa Analyst at RANE, where he focuses on strategic, demographic, social, diplomatic and political issues in the greater MENA region. His area of expertise is particularly on the behaviors of Gulf Cooperation Council member states, the Levant, Syria, Turkey, Israel, Yemen, and aspects of U.S. Middle Eastern policy. Ryan holds bachelor\u0026#39;s and master\u0026#39;s degrees from Arizona State University. He has lived and worked in the United Arab Emirates and Qatar, and has been cited as a regional expert in numerous publications, including AP, Bloomberg and Time magazine. You can follow him on Twitter at @Ryan_Bohl.\u003c/div\u003e","photo":"https://www.stratfor.com/sites/default/files/profiles/photos/Ryan_Bohl_website%20%281%29.jpg","job_title":"Senior Middle East and North Africa Analyst at RANE","organization":null,"organization_link":"","created":"1523916863","created_formatted":"Apr 16, 2018 | 22:14 GMT","changed":"1673036183","changed_formatted":"Jan 6, 2023 | 20:16 GMT","path_alias":"people/288686","status":1}],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"136","vid":"5","name":"Syria"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351793","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Has Poland Missed Its Shot at Becoming a Major EU Power?","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Poland GettyImages-2227331738.jpg","alt":"The flags of NATO, the EU and Poland are seen next to each other. ","title":"The flags of NATO, the EU and Poland are seen next to each other. ","caption":"The flags of NATO, the EU and Poland are seen next to each other.","credit":"(Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=Wh3mFIYZ","small":"16x9_small/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=KjTgfvjE","medium":"16x9_medium/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=TrAnCgQX","large":"16x9_large/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=rzuZnmnB","full":"16x9_full/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=bM7Yrqfd"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=Ctmnezv_","small":"square_small/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=QP2J3yLQ","medium":"square_medium/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=fDaYi10N","large":"square_large/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=zNL4zY-V","full":"square_full/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=4N_iOKdY"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=X_X9Nask","small":"article_small/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=NVTYkgD4","medium":"article_medium/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=GhPvdRVe","large":"article_large/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=6uGWp8DL","full":"article_full/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=FevbMYpd"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=nJ0_HP5f","small":"2x1_small/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=4UzGvGO_","medium":"2x1_medium/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=5zNClKj7","large":"2x1_large/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=VIa_RKy8","full":"2x1_full/public/Poland%20GettyImages-2227331738.jpg?itok=gm4z3J1i"}}},"teaser_body":"Despite achieving strategic indispensability and significant military power, Poland's political influence in the EU and NATO has lagged, creating a paradox in which it is critical to executing Western strategies but peripheral to decision-making.","pov":"","mailout":"Despite achieving strategic indispensability and significant military power, Poland's political influence in the EU and NATO has lagged, creating a paradox in which it is critical to executing Western strategies but peripheral to decision-making.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1769452073","created_formatted":"Jan 26, 2026 | 18:27 GMT","changed":"1769452073","changed_formatted":"Jan 26, 2026 | 18:27 GMT","path_alias":"article/has-poland-missed-its-shot-becoming-major-eu-power","article_type":{"tid":"506","vid":"30","name":"Columns"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"21","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Europe","code":"","path_alias":"/region/europe"},{"tid":"91","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Poland","code":"PL","path_alias":"/region/europe/poland"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[{"nid":"211917","full_name":"Adriano Bosoni","first_name":"Adriano","last_name":"Bosoni","type_of_profile":[{"tid":"315","vid":"14","name":"Analyst"}],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"template_id":"","summary":"As Director of Analysis at RANE, Adriano Bosoni focuses on political, social and economic issues pertaining to the European Union and the eurozone.","biography":"\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003eAdriano Bosoni is Director of Analysis at RANE. His expertise is in European politics, economics and society, EU institutions and policies, risk analysis, demographics, migratory movements, and populism. He has more than a decade of experience forecasting geopolitical events on the Continent and has also worked on Latin American and Eurasian geopolitical forecasting. \u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eMr. Bosoni holds a journalism degree from USAL (Argentina), a master\u0026#39;s degree in International Relations from the University of Bologna (Italy), and has completed postgraduate courses on globalization (London School of Economics) and business analytics (Wharton, United States). He is also a former Fulbright scholar (University of Massachusetts Amherst).\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eMr. Bosoni is frequently featured in and cited by numerous newspapers and broadcasts from around the world. He has lived and worked in several countries in Europe and the Americas and is fluent in English, Spanish and Italian. You can follow him on Twitter at @AdrianoBosoni\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e","photo":"https://www.stratfor.com/sites/default/files/profiles/photos/Adriano-Bosoni.jpg","job_title":"Director of Analysis at RANE","organization":null,"organization_link":"","created":"1414773739","created_formatted":"Oct 31, 2014 | 16:42 GMT","changed":"1677513046","changed_formatted":"Feb 27, 2023 | 15:50 GMT","path_alias":"people/211917","status":1}],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"21","vid":"5","name":"Europe"},{"tid":"91","vid":"5","name":"Poland"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351717","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"The Geopolitics of Trade: Conclusion","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png","alt":"","title":"","caption":"","credit":"(RANE, Shutterstock)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=oaoNHHyh","small":"16x9_small/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=vaxs8sLq","medium":"16x9_medium/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=DEM0xyoF","large":"16x9_large/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=QPEvTmT_","full":"16x9_full/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=Ta4nk5XU"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=mLTzm6QX","small":"square_small/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=0iSbZRe7","medium":"square_medium/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=GgCnTDWp","large":"square_large/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=6RkkBiR3","full":"square_full/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=hl-KdF6E"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=9z7Z4Th_","small":"article_small/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=48dU0cA-","medium":"article_medium/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=jLHmW5xx","large":"article_large/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=RV7KA5ut","full":"article_full/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=IHg1rISS"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=alGhoMA3","small":"2x1_small/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=5b4XG8VE","medium":"2x1_medium/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=ebZbHc-t","large":"2x1_large/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=5SrhKXQc","full":"2x1_full/public/Trade-Series-Display-02202025_16.png?itok=pGAM-46o"}}},"teaser_body":"U.S. protectionism has dramatically weakened the rules-based, multilateral trade regime established after World War II, driving governments to increasingly view trade through a national security lens rather than purely an economic one.","pov":"","mailout":"Over the past year, our trade series has highlighted how larger, less open economies gain coercive leverage through bilateral economic power, because they are less reliant on exports to smaller, more trade-dependent economies. As major powers like the United States, China and the European Union become more willing to politicize trade, they and every other country will seek to reduce their vulnerabilities to coercive protectionist measures, including by more frequently using export controls. The European Union and China, for example, are increasingly employing anti-coercion and counter-sanction tools that affect both trade and cross-border investment to deter protectionist measures and threats, going beyond traditional (i.e., WTO-compliant) anti-dumping and countervailing tariffs. This growing focus on economic security is also evident in countries’ efforts to diversify their trade ties (both imports and exports) and to reshore production of strategically important goods, such as semiconductors. In the coming years, greater geopolitical competition will continue to fuel this trend, with governments increasingly viewing trade through a national security lens rather than purely an economic one.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1768831200","created_formatted":"Jan 19, 2026 | 14:00 GMT","changed":"1768831227","changed_formatted":"Jan 19, 2026 | 14:00 GMT","path_alias":"article/geopolitics-trade-conclusion","article_type":{"tid":"506","vid":"30","name":"Columns"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United States","code":"US","path_alias":"/region/americas/united-states"},{"tid":"195","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"China","code":"CN","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/china"},{"tid":"21","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Europe","code":"","path_alias":"/region/europe"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"1853","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Global Trade","path_alias":"/topic/global-trade"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[{"nid":"340097","full_name":"Markus Jaeger","first_name":"Markus","last_name":"Jaeger","type_of_profile":[{"tid":"315","vid":"14","name":"Analyst"}],"column_type":[],"template_id":"","summary":"","biography":"\u003cp\u003eMarkus Jaeger is a Global Economy Analyst at RANE and an adjunct professor at Columbia University. Previously he worked at Deutsche Bank in New York and London where he held a variety of advisory and research roles. He has extensive experience analyzing the global economy, international trade and global capital markets, as well as sovereign and political risk issues. Markus attended the Sciences Po university in Paris, France, and holds a master\u0026#39;s degree and doctorate from the London School of Economics.\u003c/p\u003e","photo":"https://www.stratfor.com/sites/default/files/profiles/photos/Markus%20Yeager%20headshot%20final.jpg","job_title":"Global Economy Analyst at RANE","organization":null,"organization_link":"","created":"1672865795","created_formatted":"Jan 4, 2023 | 20:56 GMT","changed":"1691684338","changed_formatted":"Aug 10, 2023 | 16:18 GMT","path_alias":"people/340097","status":1}],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","name":"United States"},{"tid":"195","vid":"5","name":"China"},{"tid":"21","vid":"5","name":"Europe"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"1853","vid":"33","name":"Global Trade"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351620","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Lessons From Trump’s Use of Force Abroad in His First Year Back in Office","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Trump GettyImages-2253891367.jpg","alt":"U.S. President Donald Trump, alongside (left to right) Deputy Chief of Staff Stephen Miller, Secretary of State Marco Rubio and Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth, speaks to the press following U.S. military actions in Venezuela, at his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida, on Jan. 3, 2026.","title":"U.S. President Donald Trump, alongside (left to right) Deputy Chief of Staff Stephen Miller, Secretary of State Marco Rubio and Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth, speaks to the press following U.S. military actions in Venezuela, at his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida, on Jan. 3, 2026.","caption":"U.S. President Donald Trump, alongside (left to right) Deputy Chief of Staff Stephen Miller, Secretary of State Marco Rubio and Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth, speaks to the press following U.S. military actions in Venezuela, at his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida, on Jan. 3, 2026.","credit":"(Jim WATSON / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=XsqezErO","small":"16x9_small/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=hm0jwGVR","medium":"16x9_medium/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=YkXkcrvQ","large":"16x9_large/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=ZHPKanJu","full":"16x9_full/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=ttMEoT0Z"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=5nfM5t_F","small":"square_small/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=qVhazl-H","medium":"square_medium/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=ehbhO-M4","large":"square_large/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=z70uvLRA","full":"square_full/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=9-ccA1uo"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=m3bAfdz-","small":"article_small/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=RYR2uF5K","medium":"article_medium/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=huK5-Xe0","large":"article_large/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=blKMMMpc","full":"article_full/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=RLlM_kNg"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=qkPeYB6c","small":"2x1_small/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=EwCnCYfF","medium":"2x1_medium/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=yRLmk9rW","large":"2x1_large/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=Tktzdquv","full":"2x1_full/public/Trump%20GettyImages-2253891367.jpg?itok=_NqOY47o"}}},"teaser_body":"While Trump routinely portrays himself as unpredictable, his extensive use of U.S. military force abroad over the past year offers insight into the likely direction of his foreign policy for the remainder of his term.\r\n","pov":"","mailout":"In the first year of his second term, U.S. President Donald Trump vastly expanded the use of U.S. military force abroad, culminating in the successful Jan. 3 operation to remove Venezuelan President Nicolas Maduro. According to data from the Armed Conflict Location and Event Data Project, the Trump administration oversaw at least 626 airstrikes through the end of 2025 (a figure that does not include the Venezuela strikes), compared to the 555 strikes conducted during former President Joe Biden’s entire four-year term. This uptick in U.S. strikes around the world fits into Trump’s self-described “peace through strength” strategy, which frames aggressive actions abroad as crucial to supporting U.S. national security and political objectives. Although Trump routinely portrays himself as unpredictable -- which he considers an asset in foreign policy -- his use of force since returning to the White House reveals 10 overarching patterns.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1767913689","created_formatted":"Jan 8, 2026 | 23:08 GMT","changed":"1767934582","changed_formatted":"Jan 9, 2026 | 04:56 GMT","path_alias":"article/lessons-trump-s-use-force-abroad-his-first-year-back-office","article_type":{"tid":"506","vid":"30","name":"Columns"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":{"tid":"601","vid":"37","name":"On Security"},"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United States","code":"US","path_alias":"/region/americas/united-states"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[{"nid":"332197","full_name":"Sam Lichtenstein","first_name":"Sam","last_name":"Lichtenstein","type_of_profile":[{"tid":"315","vid":"14","name":"Analyst"}],"column_type":[],"template_id":"","summary":"","biography":"\u003cp\u003eSam Lichtenstein is\u0026nbsp;Director of Analysis at RANE, where his expertise is a wide range of international security issues. He holds a master\u0026#39;s degree from the Security Studies Program at the Georgetown University School of Foreign Service and a bachelor\u0026#39;s degree from Johns Hopkins University. Prior to joining RANE, he served for more than four years in the U.S. government, where he developed analytic expertise on various terrorism topics, including providing tactical and strategic assessments of terrorist groups\u0026#39; motivations, capabilities, plans and intentions, as well as opportunities to counter them.\u003c/p\u003e","photo":"https://www.stratfor.com/sites/default/files/profiles/photos/sam-headshot.jpg","job_title":"Director of Analysis at RANE","organization":null,"organization_link":"","created":"1609975571","created_formatted":"Jan 6, 2021 | 23:26 GMT","changed":"1673980213","changed_formatted":"Jan 17, 2023 | 18:30 GMT","path_alias":"people/332197","status":1}],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"59","vid":"5","name":"United States"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351553","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Grading Our 2025 Annual Forecast","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Forecast Scorecard GettyImages-2167764241.jpg","alt":"A NASA satellite image shows the city lights of Europe. ","title":"A NASA satellite image shows the city lights of Europe. ","caption":"A NASA satellite image shows the city lights of Europe. ","credit":"(Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=mWw33o6I","small":"16x9_small/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=wl6Zk4J1","medium":"16x9_medium/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=PIOzvrNC","large":"16x9_large/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=0kTgNrRV","full":"16x9_full/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=Qx2Vg_YG"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=q7g5cU6a","small":"square_small/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=jL16KOZF","medium":"square_medium/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=bcJ7t8QT","large":"square_large/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=_NaAlmdV","full":"square_full/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=flLaEl7P"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=LbetDni3","small":"article_small/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=aYtVnCP-","medium":"article_medium/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=y-4txBKg","large":"article_large/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=tyAcGJ6o","full":"article_full/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=UoAVLlvK"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=VrgQb8iu","small":"2x1_small/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=u5x-Q8Cb","medium":"2x1_medium/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=0kWg8u6J","large":"2x1_large/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=aMB4iQOn","full":"2x1_full/public/Forecast%20Scorecard%20GettyImages-2167764241.jpg?itok=U-A52c1c"}}},"teaser_body":"In this scorecard, we take a critical look at our hits and misses in forecasting geopolitical events over the past year.","pov":"","mailout":"At a time when forecasts are plentiful and certainty is often overstated, we strongly believe that publishing a transparent record of our accuracy is essential. This annual scorecard is a candid internal assessment of what we forecast accurately, where we missed the mark and where events unfolded in ways that challenged our underlying assumptions. This exercise is not performative. While we will celebrate our successes and further critique our missteps, the goal of this assessment is to sharpen our analytic discipline and inform the forecast for the year ahead.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1767384923","created_formatted":"Jan 2, 2026 | 20:15 GMT","changed":"1767384923","changed_formatted":"Jan 2, 2026 | 20:15 GMT","path_alias":"article/grading-our-2025-annual-forecast","article_type":{"tid":"506","vid":"30","name":"Columns"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"16","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Sub-Saharan Africa","code":"","path_alias":"/region/sub-saharan-africa"},{"tid":"17","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Americas","code":"","path_alias":"/region/americas"},{"tid":"27","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Middle East and North Africa","code":"","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa"},{"tid":"18","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Asia-Pacific","code":"","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific"},{"tid":"21","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Europe","code":"","path_alias":"/region/europe"},{"tid":"22","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Eurasia","code":"","path_alias":"/region/eurasia"},{"tid":"28","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"South Asia","code":"","path_alias":"/region/south-asia"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"1853","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Global Trade","path_alias":"/topic/global-trade"},{"tid":"1848","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Israel-Hamas Conflict","path_alias":"/topic/israel-hamas-conflict"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"},{"tid":"1840","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Russia-Ukraine Conflict","path_alias":"/topic/russia-ukraine-conflict"}],"author":[{"nid":"223295","full_name":"Amelia Harnagel","first_name":"Amelia","last_name":"Harnagel","type_of_profile":[{"tid":"315","vid":"14","name":"Analyst"}],"column_type":[],"template_id":"","summary":"","biography":"\u003cdiv\u003eAmelia Harnagel is Director of Research and Collections at Stratfor. She holds a law degree from the University of Texas, where she studied international law and energy law. She also spent a semester at the University of St. Gallen in Switzerland studying European law. During law school, she sat on the editorial boards of the Texas Review of Law and Politics and the Texas International Law Journal.\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv\u003ePrior to joining Stratfor, Ms. Harnagel worked in local and state government and on aviation law. She earned her bachelor\u0026rsquo;s degrees in history and religion from the University of Florida.\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv\u003eAREAS OF EXPERTISE\u003c/div\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eAviation law and policy\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eForeign policy law\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eEuropean law\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/div\u003e","photo":"https://www.stratfor.com/sites/default/files/profiles/photos/Amelia_Harnagel-2%20%281%29.jpg","job_title":"Director of Analytic Client Solutions","organization":null,"organization_link":"","created":"1455231046","created_formatted":"Feb 11, 2016 | 22:50 GMT","changed":"1594825755","changed_formatted":"Jul 15, 2020 | 15:09 GMT","path_alias":"people/223295","status":1}],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"16","vid":"5","name":"Sub-Saharan Africa"},{"tid":"17","vid":"5","name":"Americas"},{"tid":"27","vid":"5","name":"Middle East and North Africa"},{"tid":"18","vid":"5","name":"Asia-Pacific"},{"tid":"21","vid":"5","name":"Europe"},{"tid":"22","vid":"5","name":"Eurasia"},{"tid":"28","vid":"5","name":"South Asia"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"1853","vid":"33","name":"Global Trade"},{"tid":"1848","vid":"33","name":"Israel-Hamas Conflict"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"},{"tid":"1840","vid":"33","name":"Russia-Ukraine Conflict"},{"tid":"1661","vid":"33","name":"U.S.-China Relations"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351463","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"The Precarious Path to South Arabian Independence","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Yemen STC GettyImages-2251252896.jpg","alt":"Yemenis gather during a rally to show their support for the UAE-backed Southern Transitional Council (STC), which wants to revive an independent South Yemen, as they wave the old South Yemen flag in Khormaksar Square, in the coastal port city of Aden on Dec. 14, 2025. ","title":"Yemenis gather during a rally to show their support for the UAE-backed Southern Transitional Council (STC), which wants to revive an independent South Yemen, as they wave the old South Yemen flag in Khormaksar Square, in the coastal port city of Aden on Dec. 14, 2025. ","caption":"Yemenis gather during a rally to show their support for the UAE-backed Southern Transitional Council (STC), which wants to revive an independent South Yemen, as they wave the old South Yemen flag in Khormaksar Square, in the coastal port city of Aden on Dec. 14, 2025. ","credit":"(Saleh Al-OBEIDI / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=uP0Xu_dK","small":"16x9_small/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=_UdvbywS","medium":"16x9_medium/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=rgWbpnnl","large":"16x9_large/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=oKArtXFI","full":"16x9_full/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=BtoOQiTT"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=N_nbTRTI","small":"square_small/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=dua5CY2J","medium":"square_medium/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=5lWEGbzu","large":"square_large/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=lQwE0PQC","full":"square_full/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=9dh2NNN6"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=d4yAU2fk","small":"article_small/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=2EjGONo7","medium":"article_medium/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=XZS8AL_4","large":"article_large/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=MfNKGzS5","full":"article_full/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=lmNjh9yt"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=We8TojZt","small":"2x1_small/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=hRpP7-Ff","medium":"2x1_medium/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=UPa_edy5","large":"2x1_large/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=XoOZNZxp","full":"2x1_full/public/Yemen%20STC%20GettyImages-2251252896.jpg?itok=zXlnJS37"}}},"teaser_body":"Achieving South Arabian independence will require Yemen's Southern Transitional Council to overcome the historical challenges that have long plagued the governance of Yemen writ large, like tribalism and regionalism.","pov":"","mailout":"Yemen's Southern Transitional Council (STC) -- backed by the United Arab Emirates -- has been on a blitz across the remnants of the central government's territory. A quick glance at a Yemeni Civil War map might suggest that a returned South Yemen may be on the cusp of reemergence after three decades within a unified state. But this path to de facto independence, while increasingly viable, is still far from a sure thing -- and for the STC to achieve it, the group must balance the pillars of Yemeni geopolitics with a care that suggests a long road still lies ahead.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1766588912","created_formatted":"Dec 24, 2025 | 15:08 GMT","changed":"1766588912","changed_formatted":"Dec 24, 2025 | 15:08 GMT","path_alias":"article/precarious-path-south-arabian-independence","article_type":{"tid":"506","vid":"30","name":"Columns"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"135","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Saudi Arabia","code":"SA","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa/saudi-arabia"},{"tid":"138","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"United Arab Emirates","code":"AE","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa/united-arab-emirates"},{"tid":"139","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Yemen","code":"YE","path_alias":"/region/middle-east-and-north-africa/yemen"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[{"nid":"288686","full_name":"Ryan Bohl","first_name":"Ryan","last_name":"Bohl","type_of_profile":[{"tid":"315","vid":"14","name":"Analyst"}],"column_type":[],"template_id":"","summary":"","biography":"\u003cdiv\u003eRyan Bohl is a Senior Middle East and North Africa Analyst at RANE, where he focuses on strategic, demographic, social, diplomatic and political issues in the greater MENA region. His area of expertise is particularly on the behaviors of Gulf Cooperation Council member states, the Levant, Syria, Turkey, Israel, Yemen, and aspects of U.S. Middle Eastern policy. Ryan holds bachelor\u0026#39;s and master\u0026#39;s degrees from Arizona State University. He has lived and worked in the United Arab Emirates and Qatar, and has been cited as a regional expert in numerous publications, including AP, Bloomberg and Time magazine. You can follow him on Twitter at @Ryan_Bohl.\u003c/div\u003e","photo":"https://www.stratfor.com/sites/default/files/profiles/photos/Ryan_Bohl_website%20%281%29.jpg","job_title":"Senior Middle East and North Africa Analyst at RANE","organization":null,"organization_link":"","created":"1523916863","created_formatted":"Apr 16, 2018 | 22:14 GMT","changed":"1673036183","changed_formatted":"Jan 6, 2023 | 20:16 GMT","path_alias":"people/288686","status":1}],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"135","vid":"5","name":"Saudi Arabia"},{"tid":"138","vid":"5","name":"United Arab Emirates"},{"tid":"139","vid":"5","name":"Yemen"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0},{"nid":"351249","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Taiwan Report Highlights Evolving Security Orientation","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Taiwan GettyImages-2247931800.jpg","alt":"Taiwanese President William Lai (center), flanked by other top officials in his government, discusses plans to propose a $40 billion supplemental defense budget during a news conference in Taipei on Nov. 26, 2025.","title":"Taiwanese President William Lai (center), flanked by other top officials in his government, discusses plans to propose a $40 billion supplemental defense budget during a news conference in Taipei on Nov. 26, 2025.","caption":"Taiwanese President William Lai (center), flanked by other top officials in his government, discusses plans to propose a $40 billion supplemental defense budget during a news conference in Taipei on Nov. 26, 2025. ","credit":"(I-Hwa Cheng / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=AOuitXUa","small":"16x9_small/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=E-cDqQYk","medium":"16x9_medium/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=JoJ0cv7b","large":"16x9_large/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=oc4UYnlw","full":"16x9_full/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=qnite19C"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=F_caeUW8","small":"square_small/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=mhAwCuQb","medium":"square_medium/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=ocboGN37","large":"square_large/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=cq9sT6vU","full":"square_full/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=s_T8ntiY"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=axw5ig9w","small":"article_small/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=fbjciT8l","medium":"article_medium/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=cKFOD1BV","large":"article_large/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=geO7wad7","full":"article_full/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=Ppzq7k9N"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=lzYlBSvH","small":"2x1_small/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=u9IzvPj8","medium":"2x1_medium/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=TPCbAgcP","large":"2x1_large/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=3VsSw2x9","full":"2x1_full/public/Taiwan%20GettyImages-2247931800.jpg?itok=XjJfjYvT"}}},"teaser_body":"The 2025 Taiwan National Defense Report reflects Taipei's growing intent and tactical capabilities for deterrence by denial against a Chinese invasion, but it also highlights persistent challenges that contribute to a continually rising risk of conflict through 2028.","pov":"","mailout":"In October, Taiwan's Ministry of National Defense published its biennial National Defense Report (NDR), which describes the state of Taiwan's security environment, as well as the goals for and challenges to developing the island nation's military. The report suggests the Taiwan military's arms procurement and recruitment capabilities are growing to help it deter and defend against a Chinese invasion. But it is still unclear how well Taiwan could coordinate a whole-of-society defense effort, necessitating deeper informal ties with the West and the broadcasting of China's aggressive gray-zone activities to gain Western support. Likewise, Taiwan's ability to deter Chinese aggression shy of an invasion (e.g., a blockade) depends as much on political signals and Lai's willingness to escalate as it does on Taiwan's military capabilities. The upshot is that Taipei is demonstrating growing intent and tactical capabilities but not yet the administrative capacity to carry out a sustained defense. Moreover, perhaps ironically, the signals Taipei is trying to send to Beijing may not be received or interpreted as Taipei intends for them to be. All the while, the risks of conflict are growing.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1764872327","created_formatted":"Dec 4, 2025 | 18:18 GMT","changed":"1764872327","changed_formatted":"Dec 4, 2025 | 18:18 GMT","path_alias":"article/taiwan-report-highlights-evolving-security-orientation","article_type":{"tid":"506","vid":"30","name":"Columns"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":{"tid":"600","vid":"37","name":"On Geopolitics"},"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"195","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"China","code":"CN","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/china"},{"tid":"216","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Taiwan","code":"TW","path_alias":"/region/asia-pacific/taiwan"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Military \u0026 Security","path_alias":"/topic/military-security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"}],"author":[{"nid":"338115","full_name":"Chase Blazek","first_name":"Chase","last_name":"Blazek","type_of_profile":[{"tid":"315","vid":"14","name":"Analyst"}],"column_type":[],"template_id":"","summary":"","biography":"\u003cp\u003eChase Blazek is an Asia-Pacific Analyst at RANE, where he focuses on Chinese policy and the geopolitical impacts of China\u0026#39;s rise, as well as the shifting landscapes surrounding Hong Kong and Taiwan. Prior to joining RANE, he served with the Foreign Commercial Service at the U.S. Consulate in Chengdu, China, and worked as a Southeast Asia market analyst for the US-ASEAN Business Council. Chase holds a bachelor\u0026#39;s degree in Computer Science from the University of Nebraska-Lincoln and a master\u0026#39;s degree in International Affairs from the Bush School of Government and Public Service at Texas A\u0026amp;M University. He speaks English and Mandarin Chinese and is keen on using data analytics to explain current events. You can follow him on Twitter at @blazek_chase.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","photo":"https://www.stratfor.com/sites/default/files/profiles/photos/Chase%20Blazek%20Headshot.jpg","job_title":"Asia-Pacific Analyst at RANE","organization":null,"organization_link":"","created":"1656599705","created_formatted":"Jun 30, 2022 | 14:35 GMT","changed":"1673035978","changed_formatted":"Jan 6, 2023 | 20:12 GMT","path_alias":"people/338115","status":1}],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"195","vid":"5","name":"China"},{"tid":"216","vid":"5","name":"Taiwan"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"529","vid":"33","name":"Military \u0026 Security"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0}],"isLoadingData":false,"type":"filtered_content_feed"}],"token":null,"policy":"","interestData":{"total_count":228158,"facet_data":{"sm_tl_Risk_Categories":{"Cyber \u0026 Information Threats":673},"sm_wve_themes_topics":{"Politics":17336,"politics":17336,"Military \u0026 Security":14404,"military-and-security":14404,"Economics":10530,"economics":10530,"Energy":3510,"energy":3510,"Science \u0026 Technology":3505,"science-and-technology":3505,"COVID-19":898,"covid-19":898,"Russia-Ukraine Conflict":871,"russia-ukraine-conflict":871,"Cyber \u0026 Information":673,"cyber \u0026 information":673,"U.S.-China Relations":668,"us-china-relations":668,"Israel-Hamas Conflict":432,"israel-hamas-conflict