14T14:02:28Z"},{"nid":"352023","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Bangladesh Nationalist Party Wins Big in First Election Since 2024 Uprising","promo_image":{"uri":"public://GettyImages-2260838506 (1).jpg","alt":"A man walks past campaign posters of Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) chairman and Tarique Rahman in Dhaka on Feb. 13, 2026.","title":"A man walks past campaign posters of Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) chairman and Tarique Rahman in Dhaka on Feb. 13, 2026.","caption":"A man walks past campaign posters of Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) chairman and Tarique Rahman in Dhaka on Feb. 13, 2026.","credit":"(Sajjad HUSSAIN / AFP via Getty Images)","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=d-MzaKNt","small":"16x9_small/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=9O7YZMje","medium":"16x9_medium/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=pR7mTi6M","large":"16x9_large/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=2eXfIe25","full":"16x9_full/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=x6TUbV7a"},"square":{"tiny":"square_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=sz-jyUye","small":"square_small/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=1jg7ZNkA","medium":"square_medium/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=VEBhU4QG","large":"square_large/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=pSPPYdnq","full":"square_full/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=bEc-aHdv"},"article":{"tiny":"article_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=tfPYWcqI","small":"article_small/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=x__RaAM6","medium":"article_medium/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=3cQ0Jlgn","large":"article_large/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=LpMOzfUW","full":"article_full/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=_BpDUpt9"},"2x1":{"tiny":"2x1_tiny/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=NOtA60WM","small":"2x1_small/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=jY5ySjns","medium":"2x1_medium/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=XKjS2eY_","large":"2x1_large/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=gGXtqfc_","full":"2x1_full/public/GettyImages-2260838506%20%281%29.jpg?itok=V-_Az0ZM"}}},"teaser_body":"The transition from an interim administration will likely restore political stability, though social and fiscal pressures will still pose constraints for the new center-right government.","pov":"","mailout":"The Bangladesh Nationalist Party's election victory will strengthen political stability, while its legislative supermajority will enable the party to advance constitutional and economic reforms and pursue a foreign policy that balances ties with India and China; however, social and fiscal pressures will constrain its efforts to reform the country in the wake of the 2024 revolution. On Feb. 13, the center-right Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) announced that it won Bangladesh's Feb. 12 parliamentary elections, positioning its leader, Tarique Rahman, the son of the late former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia, to assume the premiership. As of Feb. 13, the Election Commission had not yet published the official results, but several local media outlets report that the party surpassed the 151-seat threshold needed for a simple majority in the 350-member parliament, winning an estimated 209 general seats that, when combined with seats allocated after results are confirmed, give the BNP a two-thirds supermajority. The other main contender was an Islamist party, Jamaat-e-Islami, which participated as part of an 11-party alliance that cumulatively only won an estimated 74 seats. Once the Election Commission publishes the official gazette, newly elected members of parliament are required to take their oaths within three days, formally transferring power from an interim government that has led the country for the past year and a half and enabling the formation of the new government. Alongside the parliamentary vote, Bangladeshis also approved a referendum on the interim government's proposed constitutional reforms. While this carries significant political weight and will pressure lawmakers to enact the reforms, the outcome is legally non-binding and still requires parliamentary approval to take effect.","overview":"","youtube_video_url":"","created":"1771019311","created_formatted":"Feb 13, 2026 | 21:48 GMT","changed":"1771019311","changed_formatted":"Feb 13, 2026 | 21:48 GMT","path_alias":"article/bangladesh-nationalist-party-wins-big-first-election-2024-uprising","article_type":{"tid":"502","vid":"30","name":"Assessments"},"assessments_type":[],"column_type":[],"media_type":[],"global_perspectives_type":[],"sectioned_content_type":[],"forecast_type":[],"www_public_postings_type":[],"source":"","www_site_page_type":[],"taxonomy":[{"tid":"116","vid":"5","v_name":"countries","name":"Bangladesh","code":"BD"},{"tid":"528","vid":"33","v_name":"wv_topics","name":"Economics","path_alias":"/topic/economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","v_name":"field_foundational_topics","name":"Politics","path_alias":"/topic/politics"},{"tid":"1663","vid":"33","v_name":"wve_themes_topics","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"1666","vid":"33","v_name":"wve_themes_topics","name":"Politics"},{"tid":"1666","vid":"33","v_name":"wve_foundational_themes_topics","name":"Politics"}],"author":[],"pdf":"","status":1,"premium":1,"countries":[{"tid":"116","vid":"5","name":"Bangladesh"}],"wv_topics":[{"tid":"528","vid":"33","name":"Economics"},{"tid":"530","vid":"33","name":"Politics"}],"is_bookmarked":0,"prerender_date":"2026-02-13T21:02:28Z"},{"nid":"290404","type":"article","ntype":"worldview","title":"Geopolitical Calendar","promo_image":{"uri":"public://Geopolitical Calendar Display 02212025 (1).png","alt":"","title":"","caption":"","credit":"","sizes":{"16x9":{"tiny":"16x9_tiny/public/Geopolitical%20Calendar%20Display%2002212025%20%281%29.png?itok=T9